id: pm-xo1n
title: "Add pm health 'locks' check: surface stale item-claim counts before gc is needed"
description: "pm health runs 9 checks (settings, directories, settings_values, telemetry, extensions, storage, integrity, history_drift, vectorization) but has no check for the locks/ directory. Stale item-claim locks from crashed processes silently block agents from mutating items; the only existing remedy is `pm gc --scope locks` (an explicit mutation). A read-only health check exposing active-lock count, stale-lock count, and unparseable-lock count would let agents gate on a precondition rather than running gc speculatively."
type: Feature
status: closed
priority: 2
tags[4]: agent-ux,"area:health","area:observability",reliability
created_at: "2026-06-07T10:03:18.060Z"
updated_at: "2026-06-11T21:48:30.248Z"
author: audit-observability-agent
acceptance_criteria: "- New health check name `locks` added alongside storage check.\n- Reports: active_lock_count, stale_lock_count, unreadable_lock_count, unparseable_lock_count.\n- Emits `locks_stale_count:<n>` warning when stale_lock_count > 0; emits `locks_unreadable:<n>` warning when unreadable > 0.\n- Remediation registry entries: `locks_stale_count` → `pm gc --scope locks`, `locks_unreadable` → `pm gc --scope locks --dry-run`.\n- Summarized in brief/summary health projection modes.\n- 100% unit-test coverage on the new pure-logic path."
parent: pm-5oj5
risk: low
confidence: high
resolution: fixed
expected_result: pm health had no visibility into locks/; stale item-claim locks from crashed processes silently blocked mutations and agents had to run pm gc --scope locks speculatively.
actual_result: "New 'locks' check sits right after storage in every projection mode (counts in default/full/brief, listed in summary); pure classifyLockContent extraction means gc and health share one staleness/parse policy; scanLockHealth never mutates; warnings locks_stale_count:<n> and locks_unreadable:<n> map to 'pm gc --scope locks' and 'pm gc --scope locks --dry-run' in the remediation registry and the check's remediation_map. New pure paths fully unit-tested (classifyLockContent all four outcomes incl. ttl boundary; scanLockHealth missing-dir/mixed/unreadable/ghost/readdir-error)."
comments[1]{created_at,author,text}:
  "2026-06-11T21:48:06.175Z",history-health-agent,"Implemented pm health locks check. Design: (1) lock classification extracted into pure classifyLockContent(file, raw, nowMs) in src/core/lock/lock-gc.ts (details: active | expired | unparseable_json | invalid_timestamp; the latter two roll up to the coarse 'unparseable' entry reason) — runLockGc now consumes it, so gc and health share ONE staleness/parse policy. (2) New read-only scanLockHealth(pmRoot, now?) walks locks/*.lock and counts active/stale/unreadable/unparseable; never removes anything; ghost files (ENOENT between readdir and readFile) are skipped; missing locks dir = all-zero scan. (3) health.ts buildLocksCheck inserts the 'locks' check right after storage; warnings locks_stale_count:<n> / locks_unreadable:<n>; status warn when either fires. (4) Remediation registry: locks_stale_count -> 'pm gc --scope locks', locks_unreadable -> 'pm gc --scope locks --dry-run' (disjoint codes, first-match resolver stays 100%-coverable; generic mutual-exclusivity guard in remediation-registry.spec covers them). (5) Projection: counts appear in default/full and brief (remediation_map stripped in brief); summary mode lists the check with empty details like every other check; locks is never 'skipped' so it always projects."
close_reason: "Shipped read-only pm health locks check: active/stale/unreadable/unparseable lock counts via the same classification pm gc --scope locks acts on, with locks_stale_count/locks_unreadable warnings and remediation entries."
body: "## Context\n\nFile: src/core/lock/lock-gc.ts — contains full stale-lock classification logic (ttl_seconds threshold, unreadable, unparseable, invalid_timestamp). This logic is currently only exercised via `pm gc --scope locks`.\n\nFile: src/cli/commands/health.ts line 1471 — checks array is assembled here; no locks entry exists.\n\nThe remediation registry (src/core/diagnostics/remediation.ts) also has no `locks_*` warning codes.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- New health check name `locks` added alongside storage check.\n- Reports: active_lock_count, stale_lock_count, unreadable_lock_count, unparseable_lock_count.\n- Emits `locks_stale_count:<n>` warning when stale_lock_count > 0; emits `locks_unreadable:<n>` warning when unreadable > 0.\n- Remediation registry entries: `locks_stale_count` → `pm gc --scope locks`, `locks_unreadable` → `pm gc --scope locks --dry-run`.\n- Summarized in brief/summary health projection modes.\n- 100% unit-test coverage on the new pure-logic path.\n\n## Evidence\n\nsrc/cli/commands/health.ts:1471 — checks assembled, no locks check.\nsrc/core/lock/lock-gc.ts — classification logic is reusable."
